05号旅游咨询电话：021-54725611\",\"startTime\":\"08:00\",\"location_y\":\"30.990193\",\"location_x\":\"121.335878\",\"time\":\"2017-07-18 11:45:00\",\"num\":\"30\",\"rank\":\"3A\",\"county\":\"闵行区\",\"end_time\":\"16:00\",\"initial\":\"SHHXSBY\",\"name\":\"上海韩湘水博园\",\"maxNum\":\"3000\"},{\"r_time\":\"2016\\/1\\/24 13:24:37\",\"image\":\"7027936997.jpg\",\"switch\":\"0\",\"sSD\":\"较舒适\",\"code\":\"98\",\"type\":\"暂无数据\",\"info\":\"紫海鹭缘浪漫爱情主题公园作为世界唯一一家集中西方爱情文化为一体的魔幻爱情主题公园.位于中国第三大岛\\u2014\\u2014上海崇明岛北沿公路2018号。内有普咯旺斯薰衣草，玛雅爱情神兽草泥马，以及月老桥、爱情花园、爱情博物馆、萤火虫馆等充满浪漫色彩的主题景观。在这里闻到薰衣草的芬芳，欣赏田园美景、听到鸟儿歌唱、漫步在花海中、与神兽一起运动。   现公园新增面积500多亩，总面积达800多亩，2015年公园倾力打造了人类区域、女巫区域、霍比特区域、精灵区域等充满魔幻爱情色彩的主题景观，让游客身临其境，另外公园将为新婚夫妇推出花园婚礼举办仪式，与心爱的人留下一生难忘的甜蜜的幸福回忆。咨询电话：021-59641233\",\"startTime\":\"08:00\",\"location_y\":\"31.679062\",\"location_x\":\"121.502334\",\"time\":\"2017-07-18 11:45:00\",\"num\":\"0\",\"rank\":\"3A\",\"county\":\"崇明区\",\"end_time\":\"16:30\",\"initial\":\"SHZHLYJQ\",\"name\":\"上海紫海鹭缘景区\",\"maxNum\":\"8000\"},{\"r_time\":\"2017\\/4\\/3 17:14:41\",\"image\":\"5472023040.png\",\"switch\":\"0\",\"sSD\":\"舒适\",\"code\":\"100\",\"type\":\"暂无数据\",\"info\":\"    上海音乐谷为AAA级旅游景区，同时是列入《上海市文化创意产业十二五规划》和《虹口区北外滩金融和航运服务业综合改革试点方案》的上海市重点文化创意产业聚集区。项目以\\u201C国家音乐产业基地\\u201D为中心，以海伦路、溧阳路、四平路、梧州路的围合区域为主体范围，核心区域面积约28万平方米。片区内俞泾浦、虹口港、沙泾港相交蜿蜒环绕，河道全长1200多米，并保留八座具有百年历史的桥梁，是目前上海唯一保存完整水系格局的历史文化风貌地区。至今还遗存有大量独具虹口特色的石库门建筑群，其中瑞康里和瑞庆里被列入了\\u201C上海市历史文化风貌区\\u201D名单。是上海城市演变过程中极具代表性的地理地标和文化地标。\",\"startTime\":\"00:00\",\"location_y\":\"31.260241\",\"location_x\":\"121.498023\",\"time\":\"2017-07-18 11:45:00\",\"num\":\"824\",\"rank\":\"3A\",\"county\":\"虹口区\",\"end_time\":\"23:59\",\"initial\":\"SHYYGJQ\",\"name\":\"上海音乐谷景区\",\"maxNum\":\"5710\"},{\"r_time\":\"2017\\/5\\/13 9:09:34\",\"image\":\"\",\"switch\":\"0\",\"sSD\":\"舒适\",\"code\":\"101\",\"type\":\"暂无数据\",\"info\":\"\",\"startTime\":\"09:00\",\"location_y\":\"30.935573\",\"location_x\":\"121.098791\",\"time\":\"2017-07-18 11:45:00\",\"num\":\"300\",\"rank\":\"3A\",\"county\":\"松江区\",\"end_time\":\"17:00\",\"initial\":\"SHXLHSTY\",\"name\":\"上海雪浪湖生态园\",\"maxNum\":\"13000\"}]', '2017-7-18 11:58:13', '2017-7-18 11:58:13');
INSERT INTO `tbl_data` VALUES ('135', '4', '[{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Originally, this phrase meant simply to get something done or to finish a task. However, it was later adopted by Shanghai gangsters during the 1930s and 1940s and used to mean to kill, eliminate or eighty-six someone.In recent years, this phrase has been combined into a new Shanghainese term called \\u201C拿伊做脱\\u201D (nei yi zu te), meaning literally \\u201Ckill him\\u201D or \\u201Cput him to death.\\u201DLocal fans always shout \\u201C拿伊做脱\\u201D (nei yi zu te) in stadiums when the city soccer team is playing. Though they shout in Shanghai dialect, visitors know what they mean and fans believe this call for blood can boost the home team\\\\\'s morale and performance.The phrase 做脱 (zu te), when it doesn\\\\\'t target a person or a living creature, is still used to finishing a job or having something done\",\"title\":\"做脱\",\"keyboard\":\"Finish, kill, eliminate, trounce\",\"ftitle\":\"zǔ té\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432883848\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/98.html\",\"tid\":\"98\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The first Chinese character in this phrase 咂 (ze) means to smack, sip, suck or taste, and the second 劲 (jin) means strength or energy.This phrase can be used to mean being enthusiastic or zealous about something or concentrating on doing something. It may also be used to describe someone who\\\\\'s humorous or interesting. For instance, you may say: \\u201CHe is very 咂劲 (ze jin),\\u201D meaning \\u201Che\\\\\'s a very interesting guy.\\u201D\",\"title\":\"咂劲\",\"keyboard\":\"Enthusiastic, zealous, excited, eager, interesting\",\"ftitle\":\"ze jin\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432015305\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/97.html\",\"tid\":\"97\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This phrase has two meanings. When one reads the phrase with an accent on the first character 做(zu), which is a verb, it means to form and support a family.For instance, when a young man or woman gets married, their parents always advise them to learn to 做人家 (zu in ga).Since making a living in a big city like Shanghai has never been easy, parents offer detailed advice on how to make the best use of space in their homes, how to make a reasonable budget and how to keep up appearances even when they are in a jam.In a commercial city, outward appearance or 面子 (me zi) is extremely important.So, by extension, the phrase has come to mean practicing thrift or being frugal. And carefully managing money and other resources is a tradition cherised by Shanghai people, even when they become betteroff.\",\"title\":\"做人家\",\"keyboard\":\"Form and support a family, thrift, frugality\",\"ftitle\":\"zǔ ín ga\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432015259\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/95.html\",\"tid\":\"95\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Young friends, particularly male friends, like having a mock fight among themselves. One may use his knuckle to give a light knock on another\\\\\'s head and the other may give a kick to another\\\\\'s backside. As long as it\\\\\'s not overdone, 打朋 (dang bang) or \\u201Chitting a friend\\u201D is a game among close friends asa means to maintain or even deepen their friendship.Later, the phrase came to mean making jokes or poking fun among friends, colleagues or acquaintances.Today, 打朋 (dang bang) means exactly the same. But it may also be used to mean being not serious. For instance, you may hear some Shanghainese say: \\u201CDon\\\\\'t 打朋 (dang bang) and be serious.\\u201DAlso, the phrase may refer to making a disturbance. For example, if you are doing something and don\\\\\'t want to be distracted, you may tell others: \\u201CDon\\\\\'t 打朋(dang bang), I\\\\\'m busy now.\\u201D\",\"title\":\"打朋\",\"keyboard\":\"Joke, poke fun, disturb\",\"ftitle\":\"dǎng báng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432015210\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/96.html\",\"tid\":\"96\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"In English-speaking countries, people say \\u201Cgo Dutch\\u201D or \\u201Csplit the bill\\u201D to mean to pay one\\\\\'s own expenses on a date or outing. In Shanghai, you can do the same by 劈硬柴 (pi eng za) or literally \\u201Cchopping the hard firewood.\\u201DAlthough the city first got gas for utilities nearly 150 years ago, wood-burning stoves were still used by many residents until the 1970s, and the firewood was chopped into small pieces of the same size.In the past three decades, more and more people, particularly young people. have become used to the \\u201CDutch treatment\\u201D and they use the local phrase 劈硬柴 (pi eng za) to describe it.\",\"title\":\"劈硬柴\",\"keyboard\":\"Go Dutch, split the bill\",\"ftitle\":\"pi ěng zá\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432015188\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/94.html\",\"tid\":\"94\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Like other Chinese, many Shanghai locals believe in physiognomy or face reading to reveal characteristics.And according this kind of divination, a broad and protruding forehead is not only a symbol of wisdom, but also a sign of good luck.So, if someone says that you have a \\u201Chigh forehead\\u201D in Shanghai dialect, he means you\\\\\'re a lucky dog.This term, 额角头碰天花板 (nge guo dou bang ze ti ho bei), means literally \\u201Cwith one\\\\\'s forehead hitting the ceiling of the house.\\u201DSince a forehead cannot touch the ceiling, the phrase means that someone is incredibly lucky or unexpectedly successful\",\"title\":\"额角头碰天花板\",\"keyboard\":\"Incredibly lucky, hit the jackpot\",\"ftitle\":\"ngé guó dóu bǎng zé tī hō bei\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432015108\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/93.html\",\"tid\":\"93\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"For Shanghainese, autumn is the season for fresh water hairy crabs, a delicacy. It\\\\\'s the sine qua non for a traditional family dinner celebrating the Mid-autumn Festival.Locals know how to shop for good hairy crabs in wet markets: pick the big and live crabs, never the dead ones.This is because dead crabs, called 死蟹 (xi ha) in Shanghai dialect, carry the risk of food poisoning and are less tasty.The term for a dead crab is 撑脚蟹 (cang ja ha) or a \\u201Ccrab with stretched legs.\\u201D Because of this notion of a dead crab, Shanghainese have been using the term 死蟹一只 (xi ha yi ze) or \\u201Cdead crab\\u201D to describe anything or anyone in a hopeless situation or someone doomed to failure or death.So, when you think of the phrase \\u201Cdead duck\\u201D in English, you can say 死蟹一只 (xi ha yi ze) or \\u201Ca dead crab,\\u201D instead.\",\"title\":\"死蟹一只\",\"keyboard\":\"At wit\'s ends, finished, done for, basket case, dead duck\",\"ftitle\":\"xī hā yī ze\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432015057\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/92.html\",\"tid\":\"92\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"In autumn, cricket fighting is a traditional pastime among Shanghai males, young and old.Many enjoy catching and raising the insect while some people gamble on fights. Naturally, in the cricket business, known as 赚绩 (zai jie), there are many quaint expressions and some have found their way into daily conversation. One such terms is 贰先生 (ni xi sang).贰先生 (ni xi sang) literally means Mr Number Two, originally meaning a defeated male cricket.Vanquished insects shy away from future fighting, so they can never be put in a serious fight again -- they\\\\\'re cowards.Later, the term 贰先生 (ni xi sang) came to describe any unmanly, effeminate, weak or cowardly man. Today, it\\\\\'s a synonym of the English words sissy and softie.    This literally means \\u201Cdisregarding three seven 21.\\u201D Traditionally, people in Shanghai and nearby areas used the pronunciation of \\u201C念\\u201D for figures 2 or 20. Thus, \\u201CThree seven 21\\u201D is the abbreviated version of \\u201Cthree times seven equals 21.\\u201D It comes from the Chinese Multiplication Rhymes, a mnemonic device for memorizing the multiplication tables. Almost every pupil learns it by heart. The simplest version goes: \\u201Cone one one, one two two ... two two four, two three six ... three seven 21, four seven 28 ...\\u201D This is one of the basics of arithmetic. So, if one forgets or disregards basics, he or she must be out of their mind or doing something irrational. The term 勿管三七二十一 (fo2 gwu3 san1 qi nie2 ye) suggests forgetting the usual rules or reason, doing whatever one wants, behaving in a foolhardy, reckless or audacious way. A longer version is勿管三七二十一meaning \\u201Cdisregarding whether it\\\\\'s three seven 21 or four seven 28.\\u201D    The figures 3, 6 and 9 have special meanings in Shanghai parlance. In 1917, the?Great World, China\\\\\'s earliest and most famous indoor entertainment center, opened in Shanghai. The three characters of the center\\\\\'s name \\u201C大世界\\u201D happen to have three, six and nine strokes, respectively. So, locals nicknamed it 369. Later 369 came to mean a higgledy-piggledy place or a dump. The figures 369 may also mean every now and then, or every two or three days. The figures denote the third, sixth or ninth days of a month, indicating short intervals. For instance, a couple that frequently quarrels may be described by saying, \\u201CThey fight on 369 and quibble every day.\\u201D The phrase三六九捞现钞 (san1 lo jiu3 lao1 yi3 cao1) means literally \\u201C369, grab the cash.\\u201D The jargon was first used in the city\\\\\'s stock market to mean making short-term investments, selling shares to make quick profits. Since the 1990s, it means taking every opportunity to grab fast cash.    This phrase consists of two shorter terms: 千年 and 难板. The first means \\u201Cone thousand years\\u201D and the second \\u201Crarely,\\u201D a typical Shanghainese colloquialism. People usually use 难板to describe infrequent happenings. One might say: \\u201CI难板go out to eat\\u201D or \\u201CWe live in the same compound, but we难板meet each other.\\u201D The phrase 千年难板(qi1 ni1 nei3 bei1) means \\u201Crarely in a thousand years\\u201D or \\u201Conce in a million years.\\u201D\",\"title\":\"贰先生\",\"keyboard\":\"Sissy, softie\",\"ftitle\":\"nǐ xī sàng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014968\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/91.html\",\"tid\":\"91\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This phrase literally means \\u201Cexposing the Western mirror,\\u201D referring to a street peep show popular during the first half of the 20th century. The show was staged in a big wooden box, a mirror at the top of the box reflected light coming through a few holes onto a picture displayed at the back side of the box. Viewers, usually young children, paid two cents to peep through holes in the front of the box at pictures that seemed to move -- they were manually pulled through at the back. Most depicted foreign scenery and fashionable Western ladies.Once the box fell from its stand and broke, people found that the magic show was very simple: a box, a mirror and a few pictures.Today, the phrase \\u201C拆穿西洋镜\\u201D (ce1 cu1 xi1 yang4 jing) means to see through a trick and expose the true nature of something. Another related phrase in Shanghai dialect is \\u201C看西洋镜\\u201D (kyu xi yang jing), literally \\u201Cwatching the Western mirror.\\u201D It means to get a look at the excitement or watch the fun.\",\"title\":\"拆穿西洋镜\",\"keyboard\":\"To see through a trick, figure out the true nature, strip off the camouflage\",\"ftitle\":\"cē cū xī yàng jing\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014907\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/89.html\",\"tid\":\"89\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"In the late Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), there were three celebrities -- businessman, a painter and a prostitute -- sharing the same surname \\u201CHu\\u201D in Shanghai. Naturally, their names were frequently mentioned in local gossip. So, later, talking about the three \\u201CHu\\u201D or 轧三胡 (ga sei wu) became a popular term used to describe people gossiping.That\\\\\'s one of the several etymological stories about the Shanghainese phrase 轧三胡 (ga sei wu). Another story was about a Chinese musical instrument called \\u201C二胡\\u201D or a twostringed fiddle. It\\\\\'s difficult to master the skill of playing \\u201C二胡\\u201D and someone learning the instrument could produce a lot of noise and soon lose interest in it. Irritated by the strident sound, people tended to ridicule a poor player by saying \\u201C三胡\\u201D (three-stringed fiddle) instead of \\u201C二胡\\u201D. Later, the term of playing \\u201C三胡\\u201D or 轧三胡 (ga sei wu) came to mean chatting idly or shooting the breeze.In current usage, 轧三胡 (ga sei wu) means to chat, engage in idle conversation or gossip.\",\"title\":\"轧三胡\",\"keyboard\":\"Chat, gossip, shoot the breeze\",\"ftitle\":\"gǎ sēi wu\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014904\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/90.html\",\"tid\":\"90\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This phrase, which literally means \\u201Cnow it\\u2019s straying far away from the destination,\\u201D came into use during the early 1990s, when the city started to build elevated roads and \\u201Cspaghetti\\u201D junctions to ease traffic problems.At first, cab drivers were not familiar with the new routes and often missed the right exit ramps. As a result, they had to take a long, circuitous route to get back to the right place. Annoyed passengers grumbled 迪(这)记走远了(de2 ji1 zou3 yu3 le), as they worried about being late and paying a higher fare.Today, cabbies know their way around better, but the phrase remains. It has come to mean something that has greatly deviated from its original purpose or something that has gone very wrong. It can also mean that someone has gotten into deep trouble. For instance, when someone is arrested for a serious offense, you may say he or she 迪(这)记走远了, meaning, \\u201CThis time he (she) is getting into deep trouble.\\u201D\",\"title\":\"迪(这)记走远了\",\"keyboard\":\"To take a long and circuitous route, make a big deviation, get into deep trouble\",\"ftitle\":\"dé jī zǒu yǔ le\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014838\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/88.html\",\"tid\":\"88\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This phrase refers to a unique architectural style for residential buildings in Shanghai, which combines both Chinese and Western elements. The two- or three-story townhouses, connected and arranged along lanes, first appeared in the city in the 1860s. Later, the city\\\\\'s downtown area was dominated by such residential buildings, now also known as \\u201Clane houses.\\u201DEach of such houses features a stoneframed black gate and a small front courtyard. The houses are considered a symbol of the city.In recent years, many of these buildings have been pulled down to give way to modern shopping malls, high-rise apartments and other urban projects.Xintiandi, a popular shopping, eating and entertainment complex, is comprised of renovated lane houses.\",\"title\":\"石库门\",\"keyboard\":\"Stone-framed gate\",\"ftitle\":\"zé kú men\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014805\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/87.html\",\"tid\":\"87\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"When guests are present, children sometimes become excited, talk a lot and act up. Shanghainese use the phrase 人来疯 (yin3 lei2 fong) or \\u201Cgo guest crazy\\u201D to describe such behavior.The term may also describe an adult who acts in a hyped, childish and immature manner in front of a group or crowd.\",\"title\":\"人来疯\",\"keyboard\":\"To act up, to behave childishly and excitedly in front of a group\",\"ftitle\":\"yǐn léi fong\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014780\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/86.html\",\"tid\":\"86\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This phrase, \\u201Csister-in-law ma,\\u201D reads like the name of a common housewife, but it\\\\\'s homonymous with the three Chinese words \\u201Cshopping, cleaning and cooking,\\u201D typically the main household chores.In Shanghai dialect, this term is often used to describe a \\u201Chouse husband\\u201D who is willingly to do a lot of housework to show his love and consideration for his wife. 马大嫂 (ma da sao) is the paradigm of a \\u201Cgood Shanghai man,\\u201D known for domestic skill and extreme concern for his spouse. So, a \\u201Cgood Shanghai man\\u201D or a 马大嫂 (ma da sao) husband is the dream of every Chinese woman.Shanghai men sometimes proudly tell others that they are a 马大嫂 (ma da sao) at home.\",\"title\":\"马大嫂\",\"keyboard\":\"House chore-doer, a person who does the strenuous work around the house (especia\",\"ftitle\":\"má dá sào\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014769\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/85.html\",\"tid\":\"85\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The term literally means a \\u201Cmold\\u201D that is used for forming or shaping things. But in Shanghai parlance, it is often used figuratively to mean a man who acts chivalrously and upholds justice. It may also refer to a brave man who doesn\\\\\'t flinch in face of danger or a man who is loyal to his friends and ready to help them despite difficulties.When used alone, 模子 (mu zi) always has a positive connotation. It is used to praise a man for commendable behavior. For instance, when a man lends a hand to help someone in dire trouble, despite possible risk to himself, one may call him a 模子 (mu zi).However, 模子 (mu zi) may be used to mean an ordinary person or even a low-life when it is coupled with various adjectives in the Shanghai dialect. For example, people may say someone\\\\\'s a 大模子 (du mu zi), which means a person of a big size, or 小模子 (xiao mu zi), a person of a small size.\",\"title\":\"模子\",\"keyboard\":\"A manly man, a brave man, a faithful friend\",\"ftitle\":\"mǔ zī\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014692\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/83.html\",\"tid\":\"83\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This is generally considered to be pidgin English meaning \\u201Cold class.\\u201D In the early and middle 1900s, locals called people and things related to the upper class \\u201Cold class\\u201D or 老克拉 (lao ke le). The term later came to mean anyone with sophisticated taste and extensive knowledge about the finer things in life. It can also describe things. For example, one might call a well-tailored garment 克拉斯 (ke la si) or \\u201Cclassy.\\u201DToday the term 老克拉 (lao ke le) can be used interchangeably with another Shanghai colloquialism 老懂经 (lao dong jing), which usually means someone who is knowledgeable in a given subject, one of the cognoscenti. But the second term can be shorted to 懂经 (dong jing), which becomes an adjective meaning conversant with, stylish and fashionable. So, someone who is \\u201Cvery 懂经\\u201D is someone with specialized knowledge or refined taste.In the 1960s, a special kind of shoe, with a black cloth upper and white plastic sole, became the vogue and people called them \\u201C懂经 shoes.\\u201DToday, however, these two are more often used among middle-aged and elderly locals.\",\"title\":\"老克拉\",\"keyboard\":\"High class, sophisticated, cognoscenti\",\"ftitle\":\"lǎo kē le\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014686\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/84.html\",\"tid\":\"84\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This term often describes anyone who is fussy, unreasonable and troublesome. It commonly refers to someone who kicks up a row, makes things difficult or points out faults in an antagonistic way.It can describe naughty and mischievous children. But it may also apply to highmaintenance females, either as friends or lovers. For instance, a Shanghai man might say, \\u201CMy girlfriend is a very 作 (zo) lady.\\u201D This isn\\\\\'t necessarily derogatory and may imply she is lovely in a high-maintenance manner. Some Shanghai men love high-maintenance women as long as they don\\\\\'t tear the house down.\",\"title\":\"作\",\"keyboard\":\"Make a fuss over a trifle, a highmaintenance person\",\"ftitle\":\"zǒ\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014653\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/82.html\",\"tid\":\"82\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The ox used to be common in Shanghai\\\\\'s rural areas and it has found its way into many colloquial terms. The phrase 老黄牛 (lao wang niu) combines the first character \\u201C老\\u201D (old) and the term \\u201C黄牛\\u201D (ox). The second part, \\u201C黄牛,\\u201D today often is used to mean a scalper, one who buys something cheap and resells at a high price. The most common are ticket scalpers.But when the \\u201Cox\\u201D is used with \\u201Cold,\\u201D it means a person who never keeps his promise or always says he will help you do something, but never does.Despite its negative connotation when it means an irresponsible person, the term can also be positive in describing a person who works as hard as an ox and never complains\",\"title\":\"老黄牛\",\"keyboard\":\"Irresponsible person, someone who habitually fails to keep his promises, uncompl\",\"ftitle\":\"lǎo wáng niu\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014642\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/81.html\",\"tid\":\"81\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This literally means \\u201Cgetting gravy\\u201D and describes exploiting an opportunity to reap some petty gains for free or at the expense of others. Many people say this is a signature behavior of common Shanghai urbanites who are very shrewd in business and keen on taking all possible opportunities for trivial advantages. For instance, mothers on a bus could hide their kids who exceed the height restriction to avoid buying a ticket. or, someone might queue up several times just to get more than one taste of free food sample at a promotion.While some disparage this habit, others say it\\\\\'s a sign of the \\u201Csmartness\\u201D of Shanghai locals.In current usage, the term may also mean taking liberties with women, such as touching them without their permission. Here, the term 揩油 (ka you) is a synonym of another Shanghai phrase 吃豆腐 (che do fu), meaning philandering or taking advantage of a woman.\",\"title\":\"揩油\",\"keyboard\":\"Get petty advantages, take liberties with (women)\",\"ftitle\":\"kā yóu\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014597\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/80.html\",\"tid\":\"80\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This term is a combination of the first character \\u201C老\\u201D (old) and the phrase \\u201C油条\\u201D (fried dough stick). The fried dough stick is Shanghai locals\\\\\' favorite breakfast snack. When used with food, the Chinese character \\u201C老\\u201D doesn\\\\\'t mean \\u201Cold\\u201D anymore. Instead, it means well done or overdone.In Shanghai dialect, 老油条 (lao yu diao) can be used literally to mean a well-fried or over-fried dough stick, or it can be used figuratively to mean a person who always goofs off at work or who is wily and can always find a way to avoid chores and responsibilities\",\"title\":\"老油条\",\"keyboard\":\"Slacker, wily old bird\",\"ftitle\":\"lǎo yóu diao\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014594\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/79.html\",\"tid\":\"79\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This literally means \\u201Cknocking the bamboo tube.\\u201DIn the old times, when copper coins were the main currency, people in southern China used bamboo tubes to store coins. So, instead of a \\u201Ccash register,\\u201D store clerks put bamboo tubes on the counter to stock coins.When a mafia money collector or rascal used a stick to knock the bamboo tube, it meant he was collecting a \\u201Cprotection fee\\u201D or putting the lug on the shop owner.Others say the term 敲竹杠 (kao zo gang) comes from the pidgin English \\u201Cbamboo chow chow\\u201D used more than 60 years ago. It meant beating or blackmailing someone while wielding a bamboo walking stick.Today, it may mean making someone to pay through the nose or robbing somebody blind by trickery or coercion.\",\"title\":\"敲竹杠\",\"keyboard\":\"Take advantage of someone to overcharge, fleece, put the lug on, extort\",\"ftitle\":\"kāo zó gāng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014555\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/78.html\",\"tid\":\"78\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This term, which translates literally as \\u201Ccome three,\\u201D doesn\\\\\'t have anything to do with the numeral \\u201Cthree.\\u201D Instead, some people believe it\\\\\'s a homonym for \\u201Clanshan\\u201D or \\u201Cblue dress.\\u201DLanshan, a robe with broad borders at the collar, cuffs and hem, was once the official dress for scholars who had passed the county- and provincial-level civil examinations during the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-1911) dynasties. Particularly, during the Qing Dynasty, it was decreed that the robe must be made of blue fabric.Under the imperial examination system, scholars who had passed county, provincial or imperial court tests were guaranteed official positions in governments. Influenced by the Confucian precept that \\u201Cstudy of books excels all other pursuits,\\u201D scholars all studied for the single goal of passing the exam and becoming an official. As a result, \\u201Clanshan\\u201D became a symbol of success and social status.In the Shanghai area, the word \\u201Clanshan\\u201D was gradually used to mean anyone who was capable or competent. Today, locals still use 来三 (lei sei) in this sense, but they also use it to mean something that is feasible or doable. For instance, you may hear locals ask: \\u201CLei sei va?\\u201D meaning \\u201CCan it be done?\\u201D or \\u201CCan you do it?\\u201D\",\"title\":\"来三\",\"keyboard\":\"Capable, competent, feasible, doable\",\"ftitle\":\"lěi sēi\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014546\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/77.html\",\"tid\":\"77\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This term combines the verb \\u201C轧,\\u201D meaning \\u201Croll\\u201D or \\u201Cjoin in\\u201D and \\u201Cparticipate in,\\u201D with the phrase \\u201C闹猛,\\u201D meaning \\u201Cfull of bustling activities,\\u201D \\u201Clively\\u201D or \\u201Ca noisy crowd\\u201D in colloquial Shanghainese. You can hear the phrase \\u201C闹猛\\u201D in ordinary local conversation every day, because city people just can\\\\\'t get enough hustling and bustling.So, in locals\\\\\' mind the term gives the image of squeezing into a noisy crowd and joining in the fun. However, it may also mean adding trouble. For instance, just when you have your hands full with multi-tasking, someone comes up and asks you to do something else right away. That\\\\\'s another kind of 轧闹猛(ga nao mang).\",\"title\":\"轧闹猛\",\"keyboard\":\"Join in the fun, take part in the merriment, add trouble\",\"ftitle\":\"gā náo māng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014502\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/76.html\",\"tid\":\"76\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This colloquialism literally means \\u201Cthree scares.\\u201D Many believe it comes from stories about a well-known historical figure called Niu Gao.Niu was a sworn friend of Yue Fei, one of the most respected Chinese heroes and a famous general who fought the invasion of the State of Jin during the Song Dynasty (960-1279). Niu was very strong and he wielded a pair of huge axes. In battle, almost no one could withstand his first three strikes. But after that, Niu became extremely vulnerable because the three strikes exhausted him.Later, Niu became a symbol of \\u201Cthree scares,\\u201D someone who could launch fierce initial attacks but became helpless soon afterwards. So, anyone who could fend off his initial several strikes would be the winner.In modern usage, the phrase 三吓头 (sei ha dou) is used to mean a \\u201Cpaper tiger,\\u201D which has a scary appearance, but is actually a weakling. For instance, locals often say: \\u201CDon\\\\\'t try to bluff me, you\\\\\'re but a 三吓头 (sei ha dou)!\\u201D\",\"title\":\"三吓头\",\"keyboard\":\"Bluffer, four-flusher\",\"ftitle\":\"sēi ha dou\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014497\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/75.html\",\"tid\":\"75\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Most people believe this Shanghainese term comes from the English word \\u201Cchance.\\u201D They share similar pronunciation. It is said that the term was fi rst used as jargon in playing billiards. For instance, if you leave the cue ball in a spot that benefi ts your rival, you probably would say, \\u201CHey buddy, I\\\\\'ve given you a good chance.\\u201DThis kind of cue sport was once popular among locals and there were numerous billiard clubs around the city until they gradually closed in the late 1960s. But the term has survived, although it is rarely used alone. It often appears in two common phrases \\u201C枪势足\\u201D (chang si zo) and \\u201C混枪势\\u201D (wun chang si). The former suggests \\u201Cdoing extremely well\\u201D because of either one\\\\\'s good ability or good luck. The latter means \\u201Cmuddling along,\\u201D \\u201Cdrifting along\\u201D or doing one\\\\\'s job in a perfunctory manner.\",\"title\":\"枪势\",\"keyboard\":\"Chance, ability, luck\",\"ftitle\":\"chāng sī\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014451\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/74.html\",\"tid\":\"74\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This phrase, literally meaning \\u201Cthree hands\\u201D or \\u201Cthe third hand,\\u201D refers to a pickpocket.In Chinese, there\\\\\'s a word for thief comprised of three characters for \\u201Chand.\\u201D So, in Shanghai dialect, a thief or a pickpocket is called \\u201Cthree hands,\\u201D two for the normal functions and the third for stealing.An alternative for 三只手 (sei ze sou) is 铳手 (cong sou), originally meaning a musketeer, who had to fetch gunpowder from a bag to reload a musket\",\"title\":\"三只手\",\"keyboard\":\"Five-finger, itchy palm\",\"ftitle\":\"sēi ze sǒu\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014440\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/73.html\",\"tid\":\"73\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The phrase means literally \\u201C20 percent discount for one\\\\\'s eyes.\\u201D In current usage, it is a pejorative often used to scold or deride anyone who fails to see something obvious, usually due to carelessness. For instance, if you accidently bump into someone in the street, the guy might shout, \\u201CAre your eyes at 20 percent discount (眼睛打八折)?\\u201DActually, when the phrase was fi rst used in Shanghai parlance, it referred to a person who wears glasses. If one wears a pair of glasses, they might be called \\u201Cfour eyes\\u201D by Shanghai locals with a half-humorous tone. In the past, people believed that only those with poor eyesight would wear glasses. So, when one\\\\\'s eyesight was particularly bad, people doubled the number of \\u201Ceyes\\u201D and said the person was \\u201Cwearing eight eyes.\\u201D\\u201CWearing eight eyes\\u201D sounds similar to the phrase 眼睛打八折(ngai jing da ba ze) and the sense of \\u201Cdiscount\\u201D in the latter suits very well the thoughts of business-minded locals. So, next time in this city when you see someone slipping up due to the fact that he or she misses something obvious, you may describe the person as one with discounted eyesight.\",\"title\":\"眼睛打八折\",\"keyboard\":\"Discounted eyesight, blind to the obvious\",\"ftitle\":\"ngái jīng dā bā zē\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014371\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/72.html\",\"tid\":\"72\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This phrase means literally two people wearing pants with a joint crotch. So if one wants to walk, they\\\\\'ve got to walk together. Today, it usually refers to people who work closely together for a fraudulent or deceitful purpose.\",\"title\":\"连档模子\",\"keyboard\":\"Conspirator, colluder\",\"ftitle\":\"lí dāng mǔ zī\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014326\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/71.html\",\"tid\":\"71\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"In Shanghai dialect, 蓬头 (bong dou) means a sudden puff of smoke, dust or flame. In modern usage, this phrase refers to a sudden pickup in momentum for a strategy or activity, such as the spread of a trend or sales of certain products. But it always implies a bit of hullabaloo.\",\"title\":\"起蓬头\",\"keyboard\":\"Sudden pickup, hullabaloo\",\"ftitle\":\"qí bóng dóu\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014285\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/70.html\",\"tid\":\"70\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This term originally means to sew the hem of a dress. It\\\\\'s not a big job but it is necessary to complete the garment. Later, it was used to describe some young women hired by evil merchants to help boost their shady businesses.Now it may mean offering friendly persuasion to help seal a deal. However in many cases the phrase still has a pejorative connotation. It implies a false bid or feigned enthusiasm in an attempt to dupe others into participating in a swindle, or buying a substandard or overpriced product.A related phrase is 撬边模子 (qiao bi mu zi), which means a shill or beguiler who pretends to be a satisfied customer to entice others into buying some questionable products.\",\"title\":\"撬边\",\"keyboard\":\"Friendly persuasion, false bid, shill\",\"ftitle\":\"qiāo bì\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014250\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/69.html\",\"tid\":\"69\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some people say this Shanghainese colloquialism has an origin involving tailors and brothels many decades ago, but others believe it comes from local jargon used at the mahjong table. Anyway, the phrase staged a strong comeback in the language in the late 1980s and early 1990s and has since become one of the most widely used phrases in the Shanghai dialect.The three characters in the phrase may translate verbatim as \\u201Cstir\\u201D and \\u201Cpaste,\\u201D thus offering an image of stirring something as murky as a paste or starch.Many agree the phrase reflects the mundane thinking of urban dwellers struggling to survive in the mudsill of society in a megacity like Shanghai. They can\\\\\'t afford to be ambitious or play the hero. So in many cases they just have to muddle through a thorny situation, feign ignorance or fool someone else by blurring the line between right and wrong.Today, this phrase may also be used to describe someone who\\\\\'s making irrelevant remarks or doing something in a perfunctory manner. For instance, in order to avoid offending either parties in an argument, one may refrain from making an unequivocal statement and so he goes off at a tangent.\",\"title\":\"淘浆糊\",\"keyboard\":\"Muddle through, muddle along, feign ignorance, fool\",\"ftitle\":\"dǎo jiāng wū\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014196\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/68.html\",\"tid\":\"68\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"There are little folk etymologies around about this phrase, which also appears in the standard Mandarin with a similar denotation.In Shanghai dialect, however, this term is often used to describe a person who is slovenly dressed or who pays little attention to his or her appearance. But when it is used to depict the weather, it means a wet or damp day.\",\"title\":\"邋遢\",\"keyboard\":\"Dirty, sloppy, slovenly\",\"ftitle\":\"lé tē\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014109\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/67.html\",\"tid\":\"67\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Shanghai people call pigeons 白鸽(ba ge) or \\u201Cwhite dove.\\u201D So, this term means literally \\u201Cflying a white dove.\\u201DIn the past, \\u201Cflying a white dove\\u201D meant a badger game or a fraud, particularly in trade. After showing customers the example of one\\\\\'s commodity and ensuring that the order was prepaid, the seller substituted the goods with low-quality or fake products. So, the real goods remained in the seller\\\\\'s possession.It\\\\\'s just like giving a homing pigeon to someone, but if he immediately sets the bird free, it will inevitably fly back to the original owner\\\\\'s home.Today, Shanghai dialect speakers use this phrase to describe anyone who stands someone up or eats his words. For example, people may say to someone who stood them up last time: \\u201CDon\\\\\'t you dare 放白鸽(fang ba ge) again.\\u201D\",\"title\":\"放白鸽\",\"keyboard\":\"Stand somebody up, empty talk\",\"ftitle\":\"fàng bě gē\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014066\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/66.html\",\"tid\":\"66\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Nearly a century ago, Yangjingbang (洋泾浜) was a small creek flowing into the Huangpu River, the main waterway of Shanghai. The creek separated the International Settlement and the French Concession. The French Municipal Council in 1915 decided to fill in the creek, turning it into a road named Avenue Edward VII. In 1946, the road was renamed Zhongshan Road E. and today it\\\\\'s called Yan\\\\\'an Road E.After Shanghai was opened up as a trade port in the mid-1800s, Yangjingbang Creek became a venue for Chinese and Western merchants to talk business. Most of them, of course, talked in pidgin: Chinese English or English Chinese. Later, people called the language \\u201CYangjingbang.\\u201DSome Yangjingbang English is still in use today, such as \\u201Cpeople mountain, people sea\\u201D and \\u201Clong time no see.\\u201DToday, people still use Yangjingbang to mean pidgin English or non-idiomatic use of a language. But, the term may also be used to refer to an unauthentic or poor imitation of something. For instance, when a Chinese is awkwardly handling forks and knives in a Western restaurant, people may say he is acting \\u201CYangjingbang.\\u201D\",\"title\":\"洋泾浜\",\"keyboard\":\"Pidgin English, nonstandard, poor imitation\",\"ftitle\":\"yǎng jīng bāng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432014020\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/65.html\",\"tid\":\"65\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This term means literally the long bird feathers used to decorate the helmets of warriors in Chinese operas. The movement of the feathers can indicate the mood of the actor or can be used to provide a lead for interaction among performers on the stage.So today when Shanghainese speakers say \\u201C接翎子\\u201D (je ling zi) they mean \\u201Ctake a hint\\u201D or \\u201Cfollow a lead.\\u201D When they say \\u201C豁翎子\\u201D (huo ling zi), they mean to \\u201Cgive out a hint.\\u201D However some people believe this term comes from the English word \\u201Cleads\\u201D as they share similar pronunciation and are related in their meanings.\",\"title\":\"翎子\",\"keyboard\":\"Hint, lead, suggestion\",\"ftitle\":\"lǐng zi\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432013920\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/64.html\",\"tid\":\"64\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Shanghai\\\\\'s answer to a Jack of all trades in the West is a \\u201Cthree-leg cat\\u201D as this colloquial phrase translates literally. People believe the term originates from the term \\u201C三脚猫，\\u201D or \\u201Ctreble hook boat anchor,\\u201D which was used by small boats plying local rivers. According to a story about this phrase, a martial arts performer once used the heavy anchor as a weapon to demonstrate his skill.Others later tried to do the same, but all failed. So people began to use \\u201Ctreble hook boat anchor\\u201D to describe any amateurish dabblers in martial arts.Since the \\u201Ctreble hook boat anchor\\u201D shares the same pronunciation of 三脚猫 (se ja mao) in Shanghai dialect, the \\u201Canchor\\u201D was later replaced by \\u201Ccat,\\u201D and \\u201Chooks\\u201D by \\u201Clegs.\\u201D Today, locals always use \\u201Cthree-leg cat\\u201D to describe a Jack of all trades but master of none.\",\"title\":\"三脚猫\",\"keyboard\":\"Dabbler, Jack of all trades but master of none\",\"ftitle\":\"sē jà māo\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432013832\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/63.html\",\"tid\":\"63\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"wildfire and grass together have found their way into many Chinese sayings and even poems, such as \\u201CWildfire can\\\\\'t burn them out, next spring they\\\\\'ll grow back again,\\u201D \\u201CA little spark may kindle a great fire\\u201D and \\u201Cstarting a wildfire\\u201D as in this Shanghawildfire and grass together have found their way into many Chinese sayings and even poems, such as \\u201CWildfire can\\\\\'t burn them out, next spring they\\\\\'ll grow back again,\\u201D \\u201CA little spark may kindle a great fire\\u201D and \\u201Cstarting a wildfire\\u201D as in this Shanghawildfire and grass together have found their way into many Chinese sayings and even poems, such as \\u201CWildfire can\\\\\'t burn them out, next spring they\\\\\'ll grow back again,\\u201D \\u201CA little spark may kindle a great fire\\u201D and \\u201Cstarting a wildfire\\u201D as in this Shangha\",\"title\":\"放野火\",\"keyboard\":\"Spread rumors, defame, slander\",\"ftitle\":\"fāng yǎ hu\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432006100\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/61.html\",\"tid\":\"61\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"According to the ancient Chinese divination, the weight of a person\\\\\'s bones plays a crucial role in determining his or her fortune. For instance, a person with heavier bones could become a noble, general or high-ranking official, while those with very li\",\"title\":\"轻骨头\",\"keyboard\":\"Giddy, flippant, frivolous, light-minded\",\"ftitle\":\"qīng gwō dou\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432006062\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/60.html\",\"tid\":\"60\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"In this phrase, the term 花头 (hu dou) originally means a decorative design or flower pattern. Later, it was used to mean the trick or essence of something. Today, the phrase implies subterfuge or hidden tricks. But it may also mean the attraction or a\",\"title\":\"有花头\",\"keyboard\":\"Subterfuge, capable or efficient, attraction, having an affair\",\"ftitle\":\"yǒu hū dou\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432006013\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/59.html\",\"tid\":\"59\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some people believe this Shanghainese phrase is actually a pidgin term for the English word shocking, partly because they share a similar pronunciation and partly because they are related in their meanings.So, when the phrase was first in\",\"title\":\"煞根\",\"keyboard\":\"Extreme, absolute, rock bottom\",\"ftitle\":\"sā gēn\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005955\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/58.html\",\"tid\":\"58\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Many say this is another pidgin English term widely used by Shanghai locals. This term, 促狭 (co ke), sounds very similar to the English word \\u201Ctrick\\u201D and shares some meanings of the word \\u201Ctricky.\\u201DThe Shanghainese phrase is now almost always used with a de\",\"title\":\"促狭\",\"keyboard\":\"Tricky, mean, sinister, vicious, hard to deal with\",\"ftitle\":\"cō kē\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005900\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/57.html\",\"tid\":\"57\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"In current usage, this term is used to describe any products, particularly cultural, produced with distinctive local characteristics in Shanghai. They include paintings, novels, operas, plays, fashion and cuisine. Such products all feature an avant-garde, innovative, liberal or East-Meets-West style. In the past, however, the term had a derogatory connotation.It was first introduced in the mid-1800s to describe a school of artists living in Shanghai region. Under the influence of modern business and trade, the artists produced paintings and the like depicting modern and mundane topics. In the 1930s, the term was used by scholars in the north to criticize the commercialism of their mainly Shanghai resident southern counterparts.Many famous writers were involved in vehement debates in the 1930s regarding the terms of 海派 (hei pa) and 京派 (jing pa) or \\u201CPeking style.\\u201D The latter was scorned for its close attachment to bureaucracy and the political capital. In following decades, the phrase seemed to slip into oblivion in Shanghai parlance but it made a come-back in the early 1980s. Today it is widely used in a positive sense, particularly in the eyes of locals.\",\"title\":\"海派\",\"keyboard\":\"Shanghai style, Shanghai School\",\"ftitle\":\"hēi pā\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005869\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/62.html\",\"tid\":\"62\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some people believe this term is another marriage of an English word and a Chinese character. They say the first character in the phrase comes from the English word \\u201Ccheat\\u201D and the second, \\u201C佬\\u201D, meaning a person.In the Shanghai dialect, the term is usual\",\"title\":\"赤佬\",\"keyboard\":\"ghost, devil, dude\",\"ftitle\":\"cē lāo\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005831\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/55.html\",\"tid\":\"55\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"When a native Shanghainese sees something thats filthy or disgusting, he would call it 腻心 (ni xin). The first character in the Shanghai dialectic phrase means literally \\u201Coily,\\u201D \\u201Cicky\\u201D or \\u201Cfed up.\\u201D The second character means the \\u201Cheart.\\u201D So, if you\",\"title\":\"腻心\",\"keyboard\":\"Dirty, filthy, nauseating, disgusting, revolting\",\"ftitle\":\"nǐ xīn\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005739\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/56.html\",\"tid\":\"56\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"During the 1930s and 1940s, Shanghai people began to divide the city into 上只角 (zang ze go) and 下只角 (wu ze go). The two dialectic terms translate literally the \\u201Cupper corner\\u201D and the \\u201Clower corner,\\u201D meaning the luxurious area and the rundown area, respecti\",\"title\":\"上只角，下只角\",\"keyboard\":\"Uptown, good neighborhood, nice part of town; slum, ghetto, rundown area, bad pa\",\"ftitle\":\"zǎng ze go, wǔ ze go\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005689\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/53.html\",\"tid\":\"53\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This term translates literally as \\u201Ceating incense.\\u201D Some people believe that this Shanghainese phrase came from a practice in the Northern Song Dynasty (960-1127).At that time, there was a special department in the imperial court that took care of the\",\"title\":\"吃香\",\"keyboard\":\"Popular, respected, esteemed\",\"ftitle\":\"chē shiāng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005634\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/52.html\",\"tid\":\"52\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Whenever you are in a situation that you have to \\u201Ceat humble pie\\u201D or \\u201Ceat boiled crow,\\u201D Shanghai people would instead say that you have to \\u201Ceat flatness\\u201D or 吃瘪 (che bi). This Shanghai dialectic term may also mean someone is defeated or overwhelmed. For in\",\"title\":\"吃瘪\",\"keyboard\":\"Eat humble pie, eat boiled crow, forced into submission, forced to admit defeat,\",\"ftitle\":\"chē bī\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005591\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/51.html\",\"tid\":\"51\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"In the mid-1990s, with their wallets getting fatter, Chinese people began to travel overseas and initially, neighboring countries such as Singapore, Malaysia and Thailand were the most popular destinations.During their overseas tours, they found many ne\",\"title\":\"老妖咯\",\"keyboard\":\"Outlandish, exotic, weird, gaudy\",\"ftitle\":\"láo yāo e\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005497\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/50.html\",\"tid\":\"50\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"In Shanghai dialect, this term translates literally as \\u201Ceating sour,\\u201D but it doesn\\u2019t mean eating something sour at all. It is often used to describe a situation in which one feels helpless or some people or something that one finds annoying but cannot thi\",\"title\":\"吃酸\",\"keyboard\":\"Helpless, troublesome, vexatious, thorny\",\"ftitle\":\"qī suī\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005446\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/49.html\",\"tid\":\"49\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This Shanghai phrase is said to come from the name of a hall used by ancient emperors to hold meetings, ceremonies and lectures. But the place was long lost and late comers could not figure out what it looked like and how it functioned.So, the term impl\",\"title\":\"名堂\",\"keyboard\":\"Name of the game, result, reason, trick\",\"ftitle\":\"mǐng dāng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005370\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/54.html\",\"tid\":\"54\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Shanghai locals are mostly rice eaters. So, if there\\u2019s any leftover cooked rice, they tend to 炒冷饭(cao lang vei), meaning to \\u201Cstir-fry the cold rice,\\u201D usually by adding a spoon of edible oil, a pinch of minced green onion or even an egg. As a result, 炒冷饭(c\",\"title\":\"炒冷饭\",\"keyboard\":\"Rehash, repeat old content, flogging a dead horse\",\"ftitle\":\"cǎo lǎng věi\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005318\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/48.html\",\"tid\":\"48\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Soy bean products are a favorite food of Shanghai locals. So, eating tofu, as this phrase literally means, is common at dinner tables. However when it is used figuratively, the phrase means men taking advantage of, or philandering with, women.People bel\",\"title\":\"吃豆腐\",\"keyboard\":\"Philander with or take advantage of (a woman), tease, make fun of\",\"ftitle\":\"qē dǒu vū\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005266\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/47.html\",\"tid\":\"47\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"People believe that this term is related to a bridge in neighboring Wu County. When a master was building the bridge the county magistrate passed by. The magistrate didn\\u2019t think the bridge was being built correctly and warned that it could collapse later.\",\"title\":\"笃定\",\"keyboard\":\"Confident, serene, certain, sure\",\"ftitle\":\"dō dīng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005259\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/46.html\",\"tid\":\"46\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Few people know the origin of this phrase which translates literally as \\u201Cone-day world.\\u201D However it is widely used by Shanghai dialect speakers to mean something is littered or scattered everywhere, especially in a disorderly and confused manner. It may a\",\"title\":\"一天世界\",\"keyboard\":\"Littered or scattered everywhere, a total mess, all over the place\",\"ftitle\":\"yī tī sì gà\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005223\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/45.html\",\"tid\":\"45\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"In Shanghai dialect, the Chinese character 鬼 (ghost) is pronounced \\u201Cju\\u201D instead of \\u201Cgui\\u201D as in Mandarin. So, this term means literally \\u201Cold ghost.\\u201DIn modern usage, the term is used to describe someone who is an expert in a certain field, particularly\",\"title\":\"老鬼\",\"keyboard\":\"Expert, well versed, skillful\",\"ftitle\":\"lǎo jū\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005087\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/43.html\",\"tid\":\"43\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This phrase comes from the theatrical term台型 (dei ying), meaning the image and performance of an actor or actress on stage. To win audiences, actors must pay great attention to their costumes, movements, gestures and tones during a performance. If some fa\",\"title\":\"扎台型\",\"keyboard\":\"Seek the limelight, show off, dapper\",\"ftitle\":\"zē déi yīng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432005015\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/42.html\",\"tid\":\"42\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some people believe this phrase comes from the English word \\u201Cgander\\u201D because they sound alike and share almost identical meanings. However, others argue that it is an aboriginal term. In this phrase, the first character \\u201C戆\\u201D means \\u201Cstupid or simple,\\u201D and t\",\"title\":\"戆大\",\"keyboard\":\"Idiot, fool, simpleton\",\"ftitle\":\"gǎng dū\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432004932\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/41.html\",\"tid\":\"41\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"In Shanghai dialect, people find quite a few terms and phrases that are actually portmanteaus of the English word and the Chinese character or phrase.Here, the phrase 门槛精 (men kei jing) is used by locals to mean someone who is very smart, sharp-minded o\",\"title\":\"门槛精\",\"keyboard\":\"Sharp-minded, shrewd\",\"ftitle\":\"mén kēi jīng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432004845\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/40.html\",\"tid\":\"40\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This phrase means literally \\u201C13 points.\\u201D Again, there are quite a few explanations about how the term has become such a widely used phrase among Shanghainese speakers.In pai gow, or Chinese dominoes, it\\u2019s a bummer if you take two cards that don\\u2019t add up\",\"title\":\"十三点\",\"keyboard\":\"Bubble-brained, wacky, frivolous\",\"ftitle\":\"sé sēi dī\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432004747\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/39.html\",\"tid\":\"39\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Most people believe this term originates from the nomenclature of boat transport still thriving in the Yangtze River Delta area. Others, however, argue that it derives from the English phrase \\u201Ctoo bad\\u201D as the pronunciations are similar and the meanings re\",\"title\":\"推板\",\"keyboard\":\"Low quality, substandard, indecent, short (of)\",\"ftitle\":\"tēi béi\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432004627\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/38.html\",\"tid\":\"38\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"There are several sources of this Shanghai colloquialism. One is that it derives from the calculating device, the abacus, used in stock markets for decades. Abacus in Chinese is called \\u201C算盘\\u201D or \\u201Ccalculating board,\\u201D hence \\u201C开盘\\u201D (kai bo) meaning \\u201Copening tran\",\"title\":\"洋盘\",\"keyboard\":\"Sucker, dupe, easy target\",\"ftitle\":\"yáng bō\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432004582\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/37.html\",\"tid\":\"37\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The term comes from a Suzhou colloquial phrase used to describe children playing around. Now it usually means people playing, doing something to kill time, or playing with something or someone.It has also come to mean duping, manipulating or dallying wi\",\"title\":\"白相\",\"keyboard\":\"Play, play with, dally with, dupe, manipulate\",\"ftitle\":\"bé xiāng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432004531\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/36.html\",\"tid\":\"36\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The first character means literally \\u201Cdirty\\u201D or \\u201Cfilthy,\\u201D and the second means \\u201Cthree.\\u201D In Shanghai parlance, the number three often implies a very low level or poor quality.So, by derivation, the term describes something of low quality or extremely disa\",\"title\":\"肮三\",\"keyboard\":\"Tricky, thorny, disappointing, disgraceful, shoddy\",\"ftitle\":\"āng sēi\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432004405\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/35.html\",\"tid\":\"35\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"In ancient times, the Chinese used a string of coins as a monetary unit. One string could hold 100 to 1,000 coins depending on the period and location. Here, the Shanghai dialectic phrase translates literally as \\u201Chalf a string,\\u201D indicating it\\u2019s short of a\",\"title\":\"半吊子\",\"keyboard\":\"Senseless and tactless (in speech), mealy mouthed, dabbler, smatterer, slacker,\",\"ftitle\":\"bu1 diao2 zi\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432004130\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/44.html\",\"tid\":\"44\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The term is believed to derive from another Pidgin English expression widely used in Shanghai\\\\\'s semi-colonial era more than 60 years ago. It came from sayings such as \\u201Cbeg sir,\\u201D \\u201Cbeg say\\u201D or \\u201Cempty cent\\u201D uttered by beggars or tramps wandering the city.\",\"title\":\"瘪三\",\"keyboard\":\"Bum, beggar\",\"ftitle\":\"biē sēi\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432004039\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/34.html\",\"tid\":\"34\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Pinching someone\\u2019s nose is known as an effective way to wake them up or interrupt their dreams. This Shanghai phrase means the opposite and translates literally as \\u201Chaving a dream with your nose pinched.\\u201D Since this is impossible, the phrase is used to me\",\"title\":\"捏鼻子做梦\",\"keyboard\":\"Daydream, indulge in a fantasy\",\"ftitle\":\"nyé bí do zū máng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432004011\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/33.html\",\"tid\":\"33\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The verbatim translation is \\u201Cporridge made of soaked rice\\u201D and refers to a favorite breakfast of Shanghai locals.They usually recook leftover rice from the previous day by adding water, then boiling it to get the desired consistency.Because of the pro\",\"title\":\"饭泡粥\",\"keyboard\":\"Rice recooked with water; garrulous, talkative, gasbag\",\"ftitle\":\"fàn pāo zhōu\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432003953\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/32.html\",\"tid\":\"32\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"When English speakers say \\u201Ckicking the bucket,\\u201D Shanghai locals would say \\u201C翘辫子 (qao2 bi3 zi1),\\u201D which means literally one\\\\\'s \\u201Cpigtail standing on its end or pointing upward.\\u201DThis colloquialism derives from a local phenomenon common in the mid 20th centu\",\"title\":\"翘辫子\",\"keyboard\":\"Kick the bucket, turn up one\'s toes, die\",\"ftitle\":\"qáo bǐ zī\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432003935\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/31.html\",\"tid\":\"31\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This is another signature term of the Shanghai dialect. It is believed to derive from the English word \\u201Cdear\\u201D and today is often used for women or children who speak or act in an overly gentle or endearing way to charm or emotionally trap others.When it\",\"title\":\"发嗲\",\"keyboard\":\"act coquettishly, play the woman, act like a spoiled child\",\"ftitle\":\"fā diǎ\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432003888\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/30.html\",\"tid\":\"30\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This phrase translates literally as \\u201Cdistinguishing the seedlings,\\u201D as local farmers do to determine in which field their crops are growing best.However, the term was later used to mean competing with each other for superiority or limelight.For instan\",\"title\":\"别苗头\",\"keyboard\":\"Compete, vie for superiority or limelight\",\"ftitle\":\"bí miǎo do\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432003760\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/29.html\",\"tid\":\"29\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This phrase contains two terms, \\u201Cscolding\\u201D and \\u201Cmountain gate.\\u201D The \\u201Cmountain gate\\u201D refers to the entrance to temples or monasteries which are located on steep mountains.In ancient times, such institutes were usually built in places far away from market\",\"title\":\"骂山门\",\"keyboard\":\"\",\"ftitle\":\"mǒ sēi mēng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432003640\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/27.html\",\"tid\":\"27\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The term means literally \\u201Chairy-feet son-in-law\\u201D in the Shanghai dialect. When a young woman brings her fiance to meet her parents for the first time, the young man is upgraded from a \\u201Cboyfriend\\u201D to a \\u201Chairy-feet son-in-law.\\u201D Some people say the \\u201Chairy\",\"title\":\"毛脚女婿\",\"keyboard\":\"son-in-law to-be\",\"ftitle\":\"máo jē nǚ xù\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432003595\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/28.html\",\"tid\":\"28\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This phrase has two parts: the first part 吃 (qe), meaning \\u201Ceat,\\u201D and the second part 生活 (sang wo), meaning literally \\u201Clife.\\u201D However, this does not mean \\u201Ceating up a life,\\u201D because in the vernacular, 生活 (sang wo) may also mean \\u201Cchore\\u201D or \\u201Cjob.\\u201DFor insta\",\"title\":\"吃生活\",\"keyboard\":\"To be beaten up, be hit (accidently)\",\"ftitle\":\"qē sāng wó\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432003571\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/26.html\",\"tid\":\"26\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This literally means being stuck in tangled silk threads or entwined vines. This is annoying because it usually takes great patience and painstaking effort to disentangle oneself.In the 1930s and 1940s, this might be used to imply someone was having an\",\"title\":\"牵丝攀藤\",\"keyboard\":\"To dilly-dally, move sluggishly, dawdle, linger\",\"ftitle\":\"qī sī bēi dēng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432003327\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/25.html\",\"tid\":\"25\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\" This usually means \\u201Chelp\\u201D or \\u201Cgive a hand.\\u201D But as an imperative, it tells someone to stop his or her inappropriate behavior or abandon one\\u2019s attitude. It\\u2019s like saying, \\u201CCome on!\\u201D \\u201CGive me a break\\u201D or \\u201CDon\\u2019t give me that rubbish.\\u201D To express absolute di\",\"title\":\"帮帮忙\",\"keyboard\":\"Help, give a hand, come on!, cut it out\",\"ftitle\":\"bāng bāng máng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432002790\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/24.html\",\"tid\":\"24\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Most out-of-towners believe this is the most obvious term of the Shanghai dialect. It is perhaps partly because of the resonant pronunciation of \\u201Ca la,\\u201D which makes the Shanghai language sound noisy, and partly because of a widespread egotistic image of \\u201C\",\"title\":\"阿拉\",\"keyboard\":\"I (me), we (us)\",\"ftitle\":\"ā lā\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"\",\"newstime\":\"1432002498\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/shanghaitest\\/2015-05-19\\/23.html\",\"tid\":\"23\"}]', '2017-7-18 11:58:14', '2017-7-18 11:58:14');
INSERT INTO `tbl_data` VALUES ('136', '5', '[{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This refers to an urban lifestyle that features small luxury accessories like clutch bags, belts, sunglasses and fragrances that young people buy while staying within their means.\",\"title\":\"轻奢生活\",\"keyboard\":\"light luxury life\",\"ftitle\":\"qīng shē shēng huó\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433819722\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/213.html\",\"tid\":\"213\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This refers to discomfort related to the time spent in an office building, with symptoms including headaches, dizziness and fatigue. This is attributed to poor air quality, toxic materials and electromagnetic waves.\",\"title\":\"大楼病症状\",\"keyboard\":\"sick building syndrome\",\"ftitle\":\"dà lóu bìng zhèng zhuàng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433819660\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/212.html\",\"tid\":\"212\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some people use apps for almost every aspect of their daily life, from surfing the Internet to setting up an alarm clock, watching TV to studying. They become excessively reliant on their apps to get anything done.\",\"title\":\"App依赖症\",\"keyboard\":\"app potato\",\"ftitle\":\"app yī lài zhèng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433819587\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/211.html\",\"tid\":\"211\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Consumption is reported to be less and less sex-oriented in a modern world, with men and women buying products traditionally used by the other sex. Fragrances and skin care are no longer exclusive to women.\",\"title\":\"反性别消费\",\"keyboard\":\"unisex consumption\",\"ftitle\":\"fǎn xìng bié xiāo fèi\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433819472\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/210.html\",\"tid\":\"210\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some young people have dumped the traditional habit of watching TV programs on TV itself - turning instead to computers and mobile devices like iPad and smartphones for TV programs.\",\"title\":\"零电视族\",\"keyboard\":\"TV-free clan\",\"ftitle\":\"líng diàn shì zú\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433819432\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/209.html\",\"tid\":\"209\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Refers to those who apparently look easy-going and have many friends but who have no one to confide in.\",\"title\":\"外向孤独症\",\"keyboard\":\"outgoing autism\",\"ftitle\":\"wài xiàng gū dù zhèng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433819383\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/208.html\",\"tid\":\"208\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Chinese youths have borrowed the term from game jargon to refer to the state of being fully refreshed or recovered after a failure, defeat or exhausting task.\",\"title\":\"满血复活\",\"keyboard\":\"fully refreshed\",\"ftitle\":\"mǎn xuě fù huó\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433819306\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/207.html\",\"tid\":\"207\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The habit of eating shortly before going to bed. It is often caused by work schedules as those finding it impossible to take a meal break are mostly middle-aged or young night shift workers. Some night owls also have this habit.\",\"title\":\"夜食症\",\"keyboard\":\"night eating syndrome\",\"ftitle\":\"yè shí zhèng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433819253\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/206.html\",\"tid\":\"206\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some white-collar workers feel pressure to make it to a higher rung on the career ladder after getting established in their career, and plunge into depression. \",\"title\":\"成功后抑郁\",\"keyboard\":\"post-success depression\",\"ftitle\":\"chéng gōng hòu yì yù\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433819195\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/205.html\",\"tid\":\"205\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some office workers spend a good part of their spare time responding to work-related mails or interacting with clients via social networking.\",\"title\":\"无意识加班\",\"keyboard\":\"overlooked overtime\",\"ftitle\":\"wú yì shì jiā bān\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433819143\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/204.html\",\"tid\":\"204\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"A sudden surge of Shanghai stocks recently was initially blamed on a fat-finger glitch but was later attributed to design flaws in the order execution system.\",\"title\":\"乌龙指\",\"keyboard\":\"fat finger\",\"ftitle\":\"wū lóng zhǐ\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433819106\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/203.html\",\"tid\":\"203\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"It\\u2019s shortened from \\u201Cno mobile phone phobia,\\u201D or the anxiety that users have once out of mobile phone contact.\",\"title\":\"无手机焦虑症\",\"keyboard\":\"nomophobia\",\"ftitle\":\"wú shǒu jī jiāo lǜ zhèng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433818955\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/202.html\",\"tid\":\"202\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"It refers to those who always take an optimistic outlook either at work or at home, neither grousing nor dodging work.\",\"title\":\"抬头族\",\"keyboard\":\"chin-up clan\",\"ftitle\":\"tái tóu zú\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433818719\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/201.html\",\"tid\":\"201\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The information-era habit of snubbing friends or colleagues at a party by indulging in playing with one\\u2019s smartphone. A campaign has been launched to stop phubbing.\",\"title\":\"低头症\",\"keyboard\":\"Phubbing\",\"ftitle\":\"dī tóu zhèng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433818665\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/200.html\",\"tid\":\"200\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some women are in the habit of acting or speaking in a manly manner, like removing a beer bottle cap with their teeth or frequently using four-letter words, but it doesn\\\\\'t mean they are homosexual. \",\"title\":\"女汉子\",\"keyboard\":\"manly woman\\/Fe-male\",\"ftitle\":\"nǚ hàn zi\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"complimentary\",\"newstime\":\"1433818627\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/199.html\",\"tid\":\"199\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Those who are rich in money but not in class. The term has become popular these days with the unveiling of Apple\\\\\'s new gold-colored iPhone, which some consider gaudy.\",\"title\":\"土豪\",\"keyboard\":\"Beverly hillbilly\\/rich redneck\",\"ftitle\":\"tǔ háo\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1433818585\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/198.html\",\"tid\":\"198\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The anxiety some smartphone users feel when battery power is less than one-third. They often carry a mobile charger or have a backup battery.\",\"title\":\"电量焦虑症\",\"keyboard\":\"battery anxiety\",\"ftitle\":\"diàn liàng jiāo lǜ zhèng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433818514\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/197.html\",\"tid\":\"197\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The pictures that smartphone users take of themselves and, most often, posts online for friends to comment on. \",\"title\":\"自拍照\",\"keyboard\":\"selfie\",\"ftitle\":\"zì pāi zhào\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433818474\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/196.html\",\"tid\":\"196\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Dancing in a public square is popular among middle-aged women in China, who dance to music on a stereo, which can cause noise complaints. Don\\u2019t confuse with US square dancing.\",\"title\":\"广场舞\",\"keyboard\":\"Square dance\",\"ftitle\":\"guǎng chǎng wǔ\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433818432\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/195.html\",\"tid\":\"195\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Those who shop excessively at e-commerce websites only to find what they bought is of little use. That makes them want to break the shopaholic habit by chopping off their hands (剁手 means to chop off the hands), hence the expression.\",\"title\":\"剁手党\",\"keyboard\":\"online shopaholic\",\"ftitle\":\"duò shǒu dǎng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433818363\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/194.html\",\"tid\":\"194\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"More and more Chinese fathers have joined women in buying childcare products online, in contrast to the tradition of only mothers taking care of the kids\\u2019 daily needs.\",\"title\":\"父婴时代\",\"keyboard\":\"paternal care era\",\"ftitle\":\"fù yīng shī dài\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433818319\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/193.html\",\"tid\":\"193\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Chinese President Xi Jinping was spotted queuing up, ordering and paying for a lunch at a traditional bun shop in Beijing. The event went viral after diners at the eatery took pictures and posed with Xi and posted them online. His ordering of six buns stuffed with pork, onions, green vegetables and stir-fried pig livers and intestines becomes a popular hit in the eatery, especially among tourists.\",\"title\":\"主席套餐\",\"keyboard\":\"Xi\\u2019s lunch set\",\"ftitle\":\"zhǔ xí tào cān\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433818262\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/192.html\",\"tid\":\"192\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Funu or \\u201Crotten women\\u201D refers to young women who like gay stories. The word first came from Japanese \\u201Cfujoshi,\\u201D featuring bromance in fiction, TV dramas, films and ACG (animation, comics and games). Chinese funu appeared after the third season of the BBC drama \\u201CSherlock.\\u201D It is credited for Sherlock fan fiction and video clips depicting the detectives as a couple. \",\"title\":\"中国腐女\",\"keyboard\":\"Chinese rotten women\",\"ftitle\":\"zhōng guó fǔ nǚ\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433818223\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/191.html\",\"tid\":\"191\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Symptoms of some students, usually around exam time, include aversion to textbooks, anxiety, addiction to bed and smartphones, and daydreams of passing without preparation. The symptoms are said to be contagious, hence the Chinese term.\",\"title\":\"学癌\",\"keyboard\":\"Serious school syndrome\",\"ftitle\":\"xué ái\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433818140\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/190.html\",\"tid\":\"190\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The reason that South Korean soap operas have become a hit with females these days, some people say, is that the series usually employ three killer factors: long legs (of actors and actresses), beautiful faces and wealth, unlike the typical fare of road accidents, cancer and incurable diseases.\",\"title\":\"韩剧三宝\",\"keyboard\":\"killer tactics of Korean soaps\",\"ftitle\":\"hán jù sān bǎo\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433818099\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/189.html\",\"tid\":\"189\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some people will lose no opportunity to find an electrical socket, such as in a hotel while traveling. There is an urgency to recharge their smartphones or other mobile devices since the battery runs out easily from frequent use taking selfies and chatting on social media.\",\"title\":\"插座族\",\"keyboard\":\"socket-craving tourists\",\"ftitle\":\"chā zuò zú\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433818065\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/188.html\",\"tid\":\"188\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some young people are in the habit of using smartphones in the bed in a dark room before slipping under the covers. Doctors have warned that long-time use of smartphones in the dark does damage to the cornea, as shown by reported clinical cases in the country.\",\"title\":\"手机夜游族\",\"keyboard\":\"smartphone sleepwalkers\",\"ftitle\":\"shǒu jī yè yóu zú\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433817643\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/187.html\",\"tid\":\"187\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some young people in Chinese cities intentionally put off their wedding date to get financially better prepared for matrimony though they are psychologically and romantically ready.\",\"title\":\"待婚族\",\"keyboard\":\"wed-in-wait clan\",\"ftitle\":\"dài hūn zú\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433817605\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/186.html\",\"tid\":\"186\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Young Chinese people use it to describe anyone, especially young women, who looks younger than they really are.\",\"title\":\"逆生长\",\"keyboard\":\"grow young\",\"ftitle\":\"nì shēng zhǎng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433817538\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/185.html\",\"tid\":\"185\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"A job accepted in belief that it is only a stepping stone to a better position.  \",\"title\":\"跳板工作\",\"keyboard\":\"stepping-stone job\",\"ftitle\":\"tiào bǎn gōng zuò\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433817496\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/184.html\",\"tid\":\"184\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This refers to a craving for something that can not be satisfied due to lack of money.\",\"title\":\"穷癌\",\"keyboard\":\"unsatisfied craving\",\"ftitle\":\"qióng ái\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433817448\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/183.html\",\"tid\":\"183\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some Chinese TV soap operas leave some developments or some R-rated scenes to the viewer\\u2019s imagination unwittingly or intentionally, hence the expression.\",\"title\":\"脑补剧\",\"keyboard\":\"imagination-consuming soap operas\",\"ftitle\":\"nǎo bǔ jù\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433817411\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/182.html\",\"tid\":\"182\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"When someone shows off to his or her friends anything from a newly bought bargain to a weight loss achieved in a short time, some of the friends will say, as an indirect flatter, that it is an act of courting envy. \",\"title\":\"拉仇恨\",\"keyboard\":\"to court envy\",\"ftitle\":\"lā chóu hèn\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1433817339\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/iloveshanghai\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-06-09\\/181.html\",\"tid\":\"181\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Men considered by their wives as pet dogs, expected to be ordered around and swallow physical abuse and dressing down. \",\"title\":\"宠物男\",\"keyboard\":\"pet hubby\",\"ftitle\":\"chǒng wù nán\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432105716\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/146.html\",\"tid\":\"146\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"It refers to children of businesspeople who started from scratch but made a success of it.\",\"title\":\"创二代\",\"keyboard\":\"children of startup enterpreneur\",\"ftitle\":\"chuàng èr dài\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432105676\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/145.html\",\"tid\":\"145\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Chinese young people these days use the expression to describe someone that is lovely, dreamy, cuddly, shy and beautiful. Anything lovely is also applicable. \",\"title\":\"萌萌哒\",\"keyboard\":\"cute\",\"ftitle\":\"méng méng da\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432105647\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/144.html\",\"tid\":\"144\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The Japanese slang word for \\u201Cidiot\\u201D or \\u201Cdead last.\\u201D Chinese youngsters use it to refer to a ridiculous person who is a stranger, or a funny one who is a friend.\",\"title\":\"逗比\",\"keyboard\":\"dobe\",\"ftitle\":\"dòu bī\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432105602\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/142.html\",\"tid\":\"142\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"A colloquial expression used commonly in southern Chinese coastal areas but has spread to print media thanks to the Internet.\",\"title\":\"分分钟\",\"keyboard\":\"right away\\/a fraction of a minute\",\"ftitle\":\"fēn fēn zhōng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432105568\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/141.html\",\"tid\":\"141\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Popular in the eastern China port city of Qingdao for years, it is a mask made of stretchy fabric commonly used in bathing suits.\",\"title\":\"脸基尼\",\"keyboard\":\"facekini\",\"ftitle\":\"liǎn jī ní\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432105531\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/139.html\",\"tid\":\"139\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Used in most cases to indicate some affection on the part of parents or older generation toward the child who is naughtily lovable.\",\"title\":\"熊孩子\",\"keyboard\":\"mischievous kids\",\"ftitle\":\"xióng hái zi\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432105487\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/138.html\",\"tid\":\"138\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Some operators of public accounts on WeChat pay people based on the number of clicks on articles published in the hope of boosting their potential to attract advertisers.\",\"title\":\"刷阅族\",\"keyboard\":\"hired WeChat readers\",\"ftitle\":\"shuā yuè zú\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432105450\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/137.html\",\"tid\":\"137\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Racy pictures featuring Hollywood celebrities, including A-list actresses, have been leaked through iCloud lately, triggering concerns among the public and business communities over privacy and commercial secrets.\",\"title\":\"云裸照\",\"keyboard\":\"iCloud-leaked steamy pictures\",\"ftitle\":\"yún luǒ zhào\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432105406\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/136.html\",\"tid\":\"136\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The term gets people\\u2019s attention after the sudden, tragic death of American comedian Robin Williams. Someone is depressed, but he doesn\\u2019t consciously know or accept it. They wear a smile most of the time during the day, only to put up more and more stress.\",\"title\":\"微笑抑郁症\",\"keyboard\":\"smiling depression\",\"ftitle\":\"wēi xiào yì yù zhèng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432105348\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/135.html\",\"tid\":\"135\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The expression was newly coined when Wuhan University of Science and Technology started this fall to offer limited two-bedroom suites only to those students who work the hardest to gain the privilege.\",\"title\":\"饥饿式寄宿\",\"keyboard\":\"hunger-game style boarding\",\"ftitle\":\"jī è shì jì sù\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432105305\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/134.html\",\"tid\":\"134\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The term refers to a new \\u201Csweet talk\\u201D service from Taobao, in which people can hire someone to play the role as their virtual lovers via mobile phones, sending mediumtext or voice messages as emotional support to lonely hearts. The online communication service is charged  at least 20 yuan a day. \",\"title\":\"手机恋人\",\"keyboard\":\"mobile lover\",\"ftitle\":\"shǒu jī liàn rén\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432105269\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/133.html\",\"tid\":\"133\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"As the name suggests, this term refers to a common ailment among runners, which usually causes aching pain around the kneecap.  But it can also strike any athlete who does activities that require a lot of knee bending \\u2014like jogging, biking and jumping.\",\"title\":\"跑步膝\",\"keyboard\":\"runner\\u2019s knee\",\"ftitle\":\"pǎo bù xī\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432105229\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/132.html\",\"tid\":\"132\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The term was coined following the recent shake-up in Shanxi\\u2019s leadership. Scores of senior officials were under investigation by the country\\u2019s anti-graft watchdog for \\u201Cserious violations of discipline and law,\\u201D including Vice-Governor Ren Runhou and three members of the CPC Shanxi Standing Committee. \",\"title\":\"塌方式腐败\",\"keyboard\":\"cave-in corruption\",\"ftitle\":\"tā fāng shi fǔ bài\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432105173\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/131.html\",\"tid\":\"131\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Like having phantoms in the brain, the expression is used to describe someone with an over-reactive imagination that may generate  eccentric and mismatched ideas that are difficult to pin down.\",\"title\":\"脑洞\",\"keyboard\":\"mind hole\",\"ftitle\":\"nǎo dòng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432105141\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/130.html\",\"tid\":\"130\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Small fresh meat is used to describe male actors who are young, good-looking and have good body shapes. Usually these male actors are between 12 a\",\"title\":\"小鲜肉\",\"keyboard\":\"small fresh meat\",\"ftitle\":\"xiǎo xiān ròu\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432105076\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/129.html\",\"tid\":\"129\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"This buzzword comes from quarries between  basketball fans, meaning, \\u201CYou should go and  play if you are so good at it.\\u201D It is usually said  to sarcastic fans when they are mocking players  on the court.\",\"title\":\"你行你上\",\"keyboard\":\"you can you up\",\"ftitle\":\"nǐ xíng nǐ shàng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432105023\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/128.html\",\"tid\":\"128\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"While sticky fingers is a term used for thieves,  loose fingers refers to those who can\\u2019t stop  buying things online. Such individuals quickly  regret buying things they don\\u2019t really need  when they receive the bill at the end of the  month.\",\"title\":\"手贱\",\"keyboard\":\"loose fingers\",\"ftitle\":\"shǒu jiàn\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432104983\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/127.html\",\"tid\":\"127\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Same as Add-on Card. It is a privilege offered  to the spouse, parents or children of a primary  holder of Alipay Wallet, a mobile payment app  launched by Alipay, China\\u2019s largest online  payments provider. The primary payer can  set the fee limit for an add-on account and all  expenses incurred on an add-on account are  billed to the primary account.\",\"title\":\"亲密付\",\"keyboard\":\"add-on pay\",\"ftitle\":\"qīn mì fù\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432104930\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/126.html\",\"tid\":\"126\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Old habits die hard. Knowing you  shouldn\\\\\'t do something but doing it  anyway. The expression is used to  describe some people who may find it  difficult to change or give up their accustomed  behavior, such as smoking or  procrastination.\",\"title\":\"明明病\",\"keyboard\":\"The\",\"ftitle\":\"míng míng bìng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432104876\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/125.html\",\"tid\":\"125\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"How can you flatten a woman\\\\\'s breasts  by banding them with a piece of cloth?  The expression came after The State  Administration of Press, Publication,  Radio, Film and Television halted the TV  drama \\\\\\\"Empress of China\\\\\\\", starring Fan  Bingbing, just one week after screening  due to its flamboyant and revealing  costumes. When it finally resumed for  screening, people found all the women  in play had their breasts \\\\\\\"eliminated.\\\\\\\"\",\"title\":\"抹胸\",\"keyboard\":\"banding\\/banning breasts\",\"ftitle\":\"mǒ xiōng\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432104828\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/124.html\",\"tid\":\"124\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The term refers to those entrepreneur  want-to-bes in the startup world of  today, who dream of running a business  of their own but lack either the  knowledge or experience. Many of  them fail to recognize that success  demands tenacity and commitment,  though it is always nice to say \\u201Che who  doesn\\u2019t want to be a general isn\\u2019t a  good soldier.\\u201D\",\"title\":\"创想家\",\"keyboard\":\"wantapreneur\",\"ftitle\":\"chuàng xiǎng jiā\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432104757\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/123.html\",\"tid\":\"123\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The term refers to any piece of web  content posted with the definite aim of  compelling social media users to like it  in the sense of showing that you agree  with or enjoy something by clicking the  \\u201CLike\\u201D button associated with it.\",\"title\":\"求赞贴\",\"keyboard\":\"likebait\",\"ftitle\":\"qiǔ zàn tiē\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432104622\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/122.html\",\"tid\":\"122\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The phrase refers to a physical store  where customers can go and pick up  their parcels ordered online. Amazon.  com recently opened its first bricksand-  mortar store at the Purdue University  campus in Indiana in the United  States. It calls the store a \\u201Ccustomer  order pickup and drop-off location.\\u201D\",\"title\":\"实体店\",\"keyboard\":\"bricks-and-mortar store\",\"ftitle\":\"shí tǐ diàn\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432104560\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/121.html\",\"tid\":\"121\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Literally meaning to \\u201Csnatch a red envelope,\\u201D  this has led to public concern as  China\\u2019s three major Internet companies  Baidu, Alibaba and Tencent have joined  up with businesses and gone against  tradition to give gift money to users a  week before the Spring Festival. According  to tradition, red envelopes are  handed out during the holiday.\",\"title\":\"抢红包\",\"keyboard\":\"Snatch a red envelope\",\"ftitle\":\"qiǎng hóng bāo\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432104493\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/120.html\",\"tid\":\"120\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Employees usually need to ask for permission  from their boss for leave, which  is called jia in Chinese. But on certain  occasions like the first day of work after  the Spring Festival, many employees  fail to show up to work without asking  for permission. Most cook up excuses  like flight delays, leaving the boss no  choice but to grant them the leave.  Thus the sarcastic term \\u201Cbawang jia.\\u201D  Bawang means \\u201Cdespot\\u201D in English.\",\"title\":\"霸王假\",\"keyboard\":\"fait accompli leave\",\"ftitle\":\"bà wáng jià\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432104443\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/119.html\",\"tid\":\"119\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Usually used in reference to a newly  identified ailment linked to the neck,  or bo in Chinese, after spending long  periods hunched over a smartphone  texting messages. Peering down at a  screen puts undue stress on the neck,  causing pain when it returns to its normal  position.\",\"title\":\"短信脖\",\"keyboard\":\"text neck\",\"ftitle\":\"duǎn xìn bó\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"derogatory\",\"newstime\":\"1432104395\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/118.html\",\"tid\":\"118\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"Literally meaning an electronic device  which is worn in the ear, or er in Chinese,  a hearable is some other kind of wireless  gadget incorporating a computer. To date,  one of the main applications of hearables  has been in relation to the fitness trend  seen in the wider wearables market. A  hearable will entertain you and advise you  on how to exercise right.\",\"title\":\"耳穿戴\",\"keyboard\":\"hearable\",\"ftitle\":\"ěr  chuān dài\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432104336\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/117.html\",\"tid\":\"117\"},{\"createtime\":\"2017-7-18 11:58:14\",\"smalltext\":\"The Chinese character yan refers to  people\\u2019s face, with an extended meaning  for the look, or the physical appearance  of someone or something. So \\u201Cappearance  index\\u201D is a term recently coined to  measure the good-looking, or the value of  beauty in society. Someone or something  that ranks high on the appearance index  doesn\\u2019t have to look beautiful, but must be  at least cool, trendy and decent.\",\"title\":\"颜值\",\"keyboard\":\"appearance index\",\"ftitle\":\"yán zhí\",\"remark\":\"sh\",\"titlepic\":\"neutral\",\"newstime\":\"1432104271\",\"titleurl\":\"http:\\/\\/act.shanghaicity.openservice.kankanews.com\\/talk\\/Buzz\\/words\\/2015-05-20\\/116.html\",\"tid\":\"116\"}]', '2017-7-18 11:58:14', '2017-7-18 11:58:14');
COMMIT;

